<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-factorials" original="PRECALC/modules/m49444/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
  <title>Factorials</title>

  <!-- Content summary: - Brief introdiction on what is a factorial notation - using factorial notation by expressing it as a product of decreasing integers. eg 4!=4×3×2×1=24 - Simplifying factorial expressions eg 6! / 4! -->

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Express a natural number in factorial notation</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <!-- BEGIN BORROWED CONTENT -->

<!-- Borrowed from PRECALC fs-id1165137593595: Using Factorial Notation -->
  
  <p>The formulas for some sequences include products of consecutive positive integers. <em>
        <m>n</m> factorial</em>, written as <m>n!,</m> is the product of the positive integers from 1 to <m>n.</m> For example,</p>
  
  <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>4!=4⋅3⋅2⋅1=24</mrow>
        <mrow>5!=5⋅4⋅3⋅2⋅1=120</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  
  <p>An example of formula containing a <term>factorial</term> is <m>a_{n}=(n+1)!.</m> The sixth term of the sequence can be found by substituting 6 for <m>n.</m>
    </p>
  
  <p>
      <me>a_{6}=(6+1)!=7!=7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1=5040</me>
    </p>
  
  <p>The factorial of any whole number <m>n</m> is <m>n(n-1)!</m> We can therefore also think of <m>5!</m> as <m>5⋅4!\text{ . }</m>
    </p>
  
  <insight xml:id="PRECALC-hZs0VgmdYM" original="PRECALC/modules/m49444/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>n Factorial</title>
      <p>
        <term>
          <em>n</em> factorial</term> is a mathematical operation that can be defined using a recursive formula. The factorial of <m>n,</m> denoted <m>n!,</m> is defined for a positive integer <m>n</m> as:</p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>0!=1</mrow>
          <mrow>1!=1</mrow>
          <mrow>n!=n(n-1)(n-2)⋯(2)(1)\text{ , for }n \ge 2</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>The special case <m>0!</m> is defined as <m>0!=1.</m>
      </p>
    </insight>
  
  <insight xml:id="PRECALC-iQNyvtwaNv" original="PRECALC/modules/m49444/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>
        <em>Can factorials always be found using a calculator?</em>
      </title>
      <p>
        <em>No. Factorials get large very quickly—faster than even exponential functions! When the output gets too large for the calculator, it will not be able to calculate the factorial.</em>
      </p>
    </insight>
  
  <example xml:id="PRECALC-ttYG5SMsMC" original="PRECALC/modules/m49444/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Writing the Terms of a Sequence Using Factorials</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Write the first five terms of the sequence defined by the explicit formula <m>a_{n}=\frac{5n}{(n+2)!}.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Substitute <m>n=1,n=2,</m> and so on in the formula.</p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>n=1 &amp; a_{1}=\frac{5(1)}{(1+2)!}=\frac{5}{3!}=\frac{5}{3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}=\frac{5}{6}</mrow>
            <mrow>n=2 &amp; a_{2}=\frac{5(2)}{(2+2)!}=\frac{10}{4!}=\frac{10}{4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}=\frac{5}{12}</mrow>
            <mrow>n=3 &amp; a_{3}=\frac{5(3)}{(3+2)!}=\frac{15}{5!}=\frac{15}{5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}=\frac{1}{8}</mrow>
            <mrow>n=4 &amp; a_{4}=\frac{5(4)}{(4+2)!}=\frac{20}{6!}=\frac{20}{6 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}=\frac{1}{36}</mrow>
            <mrow>n=5 &amp; a_{5}=\frac{5(5)}{(5+2)!}=\frac{25}{7!}=\frac{25}{7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}=\frac{5}{1\text{ , }008}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>The first five terms are <m>\{\frac{5}{6},\frac{5}{12},\frac{1}{8},\frac{1}{36},\frac{5}{1,008}\}.</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <insight xml:id="PRECALC-r8zUSJtoEZ" original="PRECALC/modules/m49444/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title />
      <p>Access this online resource for additional instruction and practice with sequences.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <c>xref</c>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </insight>
  
  <convention>
      <p>This section <xref ref="sec-factorials" text="title"/> is adapted from "<url href="https://github.com/openstax/osbooks-college-algebra-bundle/tree/e10e6b91143fe884c7c60dc0ad82ef23e1be0aa5/modules/m49444/index.cnxml">Using Factorial Notation</url>" in Open STAX Precalculus 2e, used under <url href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/deed.en">CC-BY-4.0</url>.</p>
    </convention>

  <!-- END BORROWED CONTENT -->
</section>
